Create the Jazz backend context once in a server-only module and reuse it across requests/jobs:

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: { type: "persistent", dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH ?? "./jazz-data" },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});

process.once("SIGTERM", async () => {
  await jazz.shutdown();
  process.exit(0);
});
```

Key constraints: install `jazz-napi` as a direct Node backend dependency; do not create a context per request; use a stable `dataPath` for durable local state; memory drivers are ephemeral and require an upstream `serverUrl`; keep `BACKEND_SECRET` and `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` server-only and never public-prefixed; use `backendSecret` for server-connected backend/request-scoped handles; and explicitly wait for the needed durability tier before returning success when persistence or sync visibility is part of the endpoint contract.

Use `null`, not `undefined`, when clearing an optional Jazz column. In Jazz updates, omitted keys and `undefined` mean “leave unchanged”.

```ts
await db.update(app.todos, todoId, {
  projectId: null,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

If the UI only needs the local optimistic clear, you can omit `.wait(...)`; keep it when the caller needs sync confirmation.

When query inputs are reactive, pass an accessor/function so the binding rebuilds the query as inputs change.

Svelte:
```ts
import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId }).orderBy("title", "asc"),
);

// read todos.current, todos.loading, todos.error
```

Solid:
```ts
import { useAll } from "jazz-tools/solid";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId() }).orderBy("title", "asc"),
}));
```

Passing an already-built query captures the current input value instead of tracking later changes.

Use `db.batch(...)` for two optimistic UI writes that should appear together locally after the callback commits, then settle as one direct batch.

```ts
const result = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
await result.wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

Use `db.transaction(...)` when the two writes must remain staged until authority acceptance and then become globally visible together.

```ts
const result = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
await result.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Use `jazz-expo`.

Actionable setup checklist:

1. Confirm versions and native mode: inspect `package.json`, `app.json`/`app.config.*`, entry point, `metro.config.*`, and native build scripts. Jazz native runtime requires an Expo development/native build, not Expo Go.
2. Add direct app dependencies: `jazz-tools`, `jazz-rn`, `expo-crypto`, `expo-secure-store`, and `metro-runtime`. Keep `jazz-rn` compatible with the installed `jazz-tools` version so React Native codegen can discover the Turbo Module.
3. Import polyfills first in the entry point, before any module imports Jazz:
```ts
import "jazz-tools/expo/polyfills";
import registerRootComponent from "expo/src/launch/registerRootComponent";
import App from "./App";

registerRootComponent(App);
```
4. Use native bindings, not browser bindings:
```tsx
import { JazzProvider, useAll, useDb, useSession } from "jazz-tools/react-native";
import { ExpoAuthSecretStore, useLocalFirstAuth } from "jazz-tools/expo";
```
5. Configure Metro with the project’s existing style, and add `withJazz` from `jazz-tools/dev/expo` if the app uses Jazz dev injection/codegen support. Preserve any required pnpm symlink handling.
6. Mount `JazzProvider` only after identity is available, and memoize config so the native client is not recreated on every render.
7. Verify with native builds: run schema/type checks, `expo prebuild` for iOS and Android if applicable, then `expo run:ios` and `expo run:android`. A successful Metro bundle alone does not prove `jazz-rn` linked.

Create the file with an edge write tier, then create the parent row and wait for edge as well, so success means both chunks and the parent reference are durable at edge:

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });

const upload = await db.insert(app.uploads, {
  owner_id: session.user_id,
  label,
  fileId: file.id,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

For download, request the tier needed by the product and handle incomplete local chunk state separately from missing access or missing rows:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  return URL.createObjectURL(blob);
} catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof IncompleteFileDataError) {
    // Show retry/syncing/corrupt-upload state based on err.reason:
    // "invalid-file-record", "missing-part", or "part-size-mismatch".
  }
  if (err instanceof FileNotFoundError) {
    // Show deleted/not-authorized/not-found state.
  }
  throw err;
}
```

If rendering with an object URL, revoke the previous URL when the blob changes and on component cleanup.

Load the parent first and keep it until file cleanup is done, because inherited delete permission depends on the parent reference. Then load the file, delete every part referenced by `file.partIds`, delete the `files` row, and only then delete the `uploads` row.

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });

if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    await db.delete(app.file_parts, partId).wait({ tier: "edge" });
  }

  await db.delete(app.files, file.id).wait({ tier: "edge" });
}

await db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

Do not delete the upload first; doing so can remove the inherited authorization needed to delete the file and chunk rows.

Build a small typed layer at the boundary, not generated table handles. Define each query projection once with `QueryBuilder`, then pair it with a strict decoder from `(ObjectId, Vec<Value>)` into an app struct.

Example shape:

```rust
struct TodoRow {
    id: ObjectId,
    title: String,
    done: bool,
    description: Option<String>,
}

const TODO_COLUMNS: &[&str] = &["title", "done", "description"];

fn decode_todo(id: ObjectId, values: &[Value]) -> Result<TodoRow, AppError> {
    match values {
        [Value::Text(title), Value::Boolean(done), Value::Null] => Ok(TodoRow {
            id,
            title: title.clone(),
            done: *done,
            description: None,
        }),
        [Value::Text(title), Value::Boolean(done), Value::Text(description)] => Ok(TodoRow {
            id,
            title: title.clone(),
            done: *done,
            description: Some(description.clone()),
        }),
        _ => Err(AppError::SchemaDecode("todos projection mismatch")),
    }
}
```

Use `SchemaBuilder`, `TableSchema::builder`, and `row_input!` for schema and writes. For inserts/updates, validate domain input before calling Jazz, then await the returned `BatchId` if the caller contract requires durability. Keep projection order and decoder order adjacent so schema drift fails loudly instead of silently corrupting meaning.

Use one long-lived backend-connected `JazzClient` in service state, then scope it per request with the authenticated caller session. The backend credential is only the service transport authority; row visibility, write policy, and authorship should come from `client.for_session(session)`.

Endpoint flow:

```rust
async fn update_todo(
    State(state): State<AppState>,
    auth: VerifiedCaller,
    Path(id): Path<ObjectId>,
    Json(input): Json<UpdateTodoBody>,
) -> Result<Json<TodoRow>, AppError> {
    let session = Session::from_subject(auth.subject);
    let db = state.jazz.for_session(session);

    validate_update(&input)?;

    let batch = db.update(
        id,
        vec![("done".to_string(), Value::Boolean(input.done))],
    )?;

    tokio::time::timeout(
        state.edge_timeout,
        db.wait_for_batch(batch, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer),
    )
    .await
    .map_err(|_| AppError::DurabilityTimeout)??;

    let rows = db.query(todo_by_id_query(id)).await?;
    let Some((row_id, values)) = rows.into_iter().next() else {
        return Err(AppError::NotFound);
    };

    Ok(Json(decode_todo(row_id, &values)?))
}
```

Map errors deliberately: invalid or missing auth to `401`, bad input to `400`/`422`, absent or policy-filtered rows to `404`, policy rejection to `403`, durability timeout to `503`/`504`, and positional decode mismatch to an internal error with safe diagnostics. Do not return success before the promised `EdgeServer` or `GlobalServer` tier settles.

Use a black-box topology with a real `JazzServer`, independent clients, and the production router. Do not duplicate route logic in the test.

Test sketch:

```rust
#[tokio::test]
async fn update_preserves_creator_and_attributes_updater_to_caller() {
    let schema = build_schema_with_permissions();
    let issuer = TestJwtIssuer::start().await;
    let server = JazzServer::start_test(schema.clone(), issuer.jwks()).await;

    let service_client = JazzClient::connect(service_context(&server)).await.unwrap();
    let app = build_router(AppState { jazz: service_client.clone(), edge_timeout: TEST_TIMEOUT });

    let alice = JazzClient::connect(user_context(&server, issuer.token_for("alice"))).await.unwrap();
    let bob_token = issuer.token_for("bob");
    let mallory_token = issuer.token_for("mallory");

    let (todo_id, _, batch) = alice
        .insert("todos", row_input!("title" => "Ship", "done" => false))
        .unwrap();
    alice.wait_for_batch(batch, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer).await.unwrap();

    let response = call_router_with_bearer(&app, bob_token, todo_id, json!({ "done": true })).await;
    assert_eq!(response.status(), StatusCode::OK);

    let bob = JazzClient::connect(user_context(&server, issuer.token_for("bob"))).await.unwrap();
    wait_for_query(&bob, todo_by_id_query(todo_id), |rows| row_done(rows)).await;

    let fresh = JazzClient::connect(user_context(&server, issuer.token_for("bob"))).await.unwrap();
    let row = query_todo_with_provenance(&fresh, todo_id).await.unwrap();
    assert_eq!(row.done, true);
    assert_eq!(row.created_by, "alice");
    assert_eq!(row.updated_by, "bob");

    let denied = call_router_with_bearer(&app, mallory_token, todo_id, json!({ "done": false })).await;
    assert!(matches!(denied.status(), StatusCode::FORBIDDEN | StatusCode::NOT_FOUND));

    fresh.shutdown().await;
    bob.shutdown().await;
    alice.shutdown().await;
    service_client.shutdown().await;
    server.shutdown().await;
    issuer.shutdown().await;
}
```

Assertions should observe public behavior: route status, settled batches, visible query state, and selected provenance columns. Use `wait_for_query` or bounded retry helpers, not fixed sleeps, and close every client/server/listener/subscription the public API exposes.

Use a real local sync topology and make the assertion order-independent. Insert several rows from Alice, wait for edge durability, then poll Bob until he sees the same set. Do not compare raw array order unless the query explicitly orders rows.

```ts
it("syncs several todos deterministically without relying on row order", async () => {
  const server = await startLocalJazzServer({ inMemory: true });
  let alice: Db | undefined;
  let bob: Db | undefined;

  try {
    alice = await createDb({
      appId: server.appId,
      serverUrl: server.url,
      adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
      driver: { type: "memory" },
    });
    bob = await createDb({
      appId: server.appId,
      serverUrl: server.url,
      adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
      driver: { type: "memory" },
    });

    const expected = ["alpha", "bravo", "charlie"];

    await Promise.all(
      expected.map((title) =>
        alice!.insert(app.todos, { title, done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
      ),
    );

    await vi.waitFor(async () => {
      const rows = await bob!.all(app.todos, { tier: "edge" });
      expect(rows.map((row) => row.title).sort()).toEqual([...expected].sort());
    });
  } finally {
    await alice?.shutdown();
    await bob?.shutdown();
    await server.stop();
  }
});
```

If row order becomes product behavior, add an explicit `orderBy` to the query and assert that order directly.

Use `createPolicyTestApp` so the test exercises the public permission layer. Assert denied reads by absence, and denied writes with `expectDenied`.

```ts
import { createPolicyTestApp, type PolicyTestApp } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { afterEach, beforeEach, describe, expect, it } from "vitest";
import permissions from "../permissions";
import { app } from "../schema";

let testApp: PolicyTestApp;

beforeEach(async () => {
  testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await testApp.shutdown();
});

it("denies Bob read and write access to Alice's row", async () => {
  const alice = testApp.as({
    user_id: "alice",
    claims: {},
    authMode: "local-first",
  });
  const bob = testApp.as({
    user_id: "bob",
    claims: {},
    authMode: "local-first",
  });

  const row = alice.insert(app.todos, {
    title: "Alice private row",
    done: false,
  }).value;

  await expect(alice.all(app.todos.where({ id: row.id }))).resolves.toHaveLength(1);
  await expect(bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: row.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);

  bob.expectDenied((db) =>
    db.update(app.todos, row.id, { title: "Bob should not write" }),
  );

  alice.expectAllowed((db) =>
    db.update(app.todos, row.id, { title: "Alice can still write" }),
  );
});
```

This assumes the policy is ownership-based, for example using `$createdBy` or equivalent creator-managed permissions.
